https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Manipulated_Man#cite_note-8
The Manipulated Man
The Manipulated Man (German: Der Dressierte Mann) is a 1971 book by author Esther Vilar. The main idea behind the book is that women are not oppressed by men but rather control men to their advantage. A third edition of the book was released in January 2009.
21:59
The book has been removed from Amazon in both printed and digital form, while the original german edition (Der Dressierte Mann) and other works from the author can still be found as of July 31, 2021. Neither Amazon nor the publisher (Pinter & Martin at least in the United States) have publicly explained the reasons for the removal. It should be noted the bookstore has been criticized in the past for banning books that featured controversial contents.[8]

–ï—Ç–æ –µ–¥–Ω–æ summary –æ—Ç trp Chapter One Most all humans are born among a family, controlled from a young age, over time some gain freedom, but typically they maintain the disposition towards being controlled. Of course every family is different. Chapter Two Of those used to being controlled, it is easier to control them. When dominance is established if treated correctly they will have no reason to hate(more on this later). "A position of dominance ensures submission through rewards for submission, i.e., by appealing to the other's desire for pleasure." Forget not that change will influence more change. Chapter Three Of those used to freedom, difficulties lie in their loyalty towards the authority. "Nobody can fault you for being loyal to your own, up-front, stated self interest before anything else." They are quick to rid of one man, for the grass is greener on the other side. On maintaining these people it is a war not just a battle, each success reinforcing their loyalty to you, it is wise to keep checks on these ones. By covertly eliminating their freedoms, their ability to rebel will be deminished. Place their freedoms in your own hands, so if they betray you they lose those freedoms. Watch the body language, tone, and actions they take, as this could be your only warning against a fading ally. Be careful of the freedoms you give, as Machiavelli states "He who helps another man to power is setting himself up for ruin, because that power has been brought about by either dilegence or force, both of which are suspect to the man who has newly become powerful" Chapter Four Of taking loyalties and turning them into your own, simply put some are more loyal then others. Of those with little loyalty, it is easier to change their loyalty to your own, but dont be quick to trust these people. And of those loyal, there is much work to change their loyalties, but once you obtain this, it will be easier to maintain.
 (edited)
15:13
Chapter Five On those accustomed to freedom, there are three ways of securing authority. - Destroy the freedom - Maintain checks on them - To allow it to continue In these days none of these three choices would be optimal, id suggest undercutting their freedoms covertly and strategically, and placing the control of the freedoms in your own hands. Chapter Six/Seven As you have already begun with your path in TRP it is wise to follow the actions of the success stories. There are multiple ways to obtain a loyalty, I will discuss two, of those obtained by fortune and those obtained through abilities. "He who has relied less on good fortune to acquire his principality has a better prospect of keeping it". Of those obtained through skill, if he continues to maintain authority and his abilities, he will have little chance of loss. Rely on your own power! ----------MAINTAINING-------------- Chapter Ten On keeping loyalties we must determine if we can keep them without the assitance of any others. Of those who cannot he must stock up so that at least he projects safety. Those who see this safety will be less likely to betray. At all times, he must instill in them the fear of the faults of a lesser authority. Chapter Twelve "The primary foundation of all states---new, old, or mixed---is good laws and a good army." So in our times I would compare the laws to their respect towards you, and a army, your ability to be the best. It matters not if your the best if they have no respect, and how can they truly respect a "weak" leader.
